\meta{version}{"1.0"}

\meta{description}{ISO/IEC 27001:2022 is the international standard for establishing, implementing, maintaining, and continually improving an Information Security Management System (ISMS). This skill covers the complete}

\subtree{
\title{Implementing ISO 27001 Information Security Management}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{ISO/IEC 27001:2022 is the international standard for establishing, implementing, maintaining, and continually improving an Information Security Management System (ISMS). This skill covers the complete lifecycle from scoping through certification, including Annex A control selection, risk assessment methodology, Statement of Applicability (SoA) creation, and continuous improvement processes.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{When deploying or configuring implementing iso 27001 information security management capabilities in your environment}
\li{When establishing security controls aligned to compliance requirements}
\li{When building or improving security architecture for this domain}
\li{When conducting security assessments that require this implementation}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{Understanding of information security principles and risk management concepts}
\li{Familiarity with organizational governance structures and business processes}
\li{Knowledge of IT infrastructure, network architecture, and data flows}
\li{Access to ISO/IEC 27001:2022 and ISO/IEC 27002:2022 standards documents}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Concepts}
\subtree{
\title{ISMS Clauses (4-10)}
\p{The management system requirements define \strong{what} must be done:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Clause 4 - Context of the Organization}: Define scope, interested parties, and internal/external issues}
\li{\strong{Clause 5 - Leadership}: Top management commitment, information security policy, roles and responsibilities}
\li{\strong{Clause 6 - Planning}: Risk assessment process, risk treatment plan, information security objectives}
\li{\strong{Clause 7 - Support}: Resources, competence, awareness, communication, documented information}
\li{\strong{Clause 8 - Operation}: Operational planning, risk assessment execution, risk treatment implementation}
\li{\strong{Clause 9 - Performance Evaluation}: Monitoring, measurement, internal audit, management review}
\li{\strong{Clause 10 - Improvement}: Nonconformities, corrective actions, continual improvement}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Annex A Controls (2022 Edition)}
\p{The 2022 revision restructured 93 controls into four categories:}

\pre{\startverb
| Category | Controls | Examples |
|----------|----------|----------|
| Organizational (A.5) | 37 controls | Policies, roles, threat intelligence, cloud security |
| People (A.6) | 8 controls | Screening, awareness, remote working, reporting |
| Physical (A.7) | 14 controls | Perimeters, entry controls, equipment security |
| Technological (A.8) | 34 controls | Access control, cryptography, logging, secure development |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{New Controls in 2022 Edition}
\p{11 new controls were added:}

\ol{
\li{A.5.7 - Threat Intelligence}
\li{A.5.23 - Information Security for Cloud Services}
\li{A.5.30 - ICT Readiness for Business Continuity}
\li{A.7.4 - Physical Security Monitoring}
\li{A.8.9 - Configuration Management}
\li{A.8.10 - Information Deletion}
\li{A.8.11 - Data Masking}
\li{A.8.12 - Data Leakage Prevention}
\li{A.8.16 - Monitoring Activities}
\li{A.8.23 - Web Filtering}
\li{A.8.28 - Secure Coding}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\subtree{
\title{Phase 1: Gap Analysis and Scoping (Weeks 1-4)}
\ol{
\li{Define ISMS scope boundaries (locations, business units, systems)}
\li{Identify interested parties and their requirements}
\li{Perform gap analysis against ISO 27001:2022 requirements}
\li{Document internal and external context (PESTLE, SWOT)}
\li{Obtain top management commitment and allocate budget}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 2: Risk Assessment (Weeks 5-10)}
\ol{
\li{Define risk assessment methodology (asset-based, scenario-based, or hybrid)}
\li{Create asset inventory covering information, people, processes, technology}
\li{Identify threats and vulnerabilities for each asset}
\li{Assess risk likelihood and impact using defined criteria}
\li{Calculate risk levels and determine risk treatment options (mitigate, accept, transfer, avoid)}
\li{Develop Risk Treatment Plan (RTP)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 3: Control Selection and SoA (Weeks 11-14)}
\ol{
\li{Map risk treatments to Annex A controls}
\li{Create Statement of Applicability (SoA) documenting:}
\li{Which controls are applicable and justification}
\li{Which controls are excluded and justification}
\li{Implementation status of each control}
\li{Design control implementation plans with owners and timelines}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 4: Implementation (Weeks 15-30)}
\ol{
\li{Develop and approve information security policy}
\li{Implement selected Annex A controls}
\li{Create mandatory documented procedures:}
\li{Information Security Policy (A.5.1)}
\li{Risk Assessment Process (Clause 6.1.2)}
\li{Risk Treatment Process (Clause 6.1.3)}
\li{Internal Audit Programme (Clause 9.2)}
\li{Management Review Process (Clause 9.3)}
\li{Corrective Action Procedure (Clause 10.1)}
\li{Deploy technical controls and security tooling}
\li{Conduct security awareness training for all personnel}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 5: Internal Audit and Management Review (Weeks 31-36)}
\ol{
\li{Plan and execute internal audit programme covering all clauses and applicable controls}
\li{Document audit findings and nonconformities}
\li{Implement corrective actions with root cause analysis}
\li{Conduct management review covering:}
\li{Status of previous actions}
\li{Changes in internal/external issues}
\li{Information security performance metrics}
\li{Audit results and risk assessment outcomes}
\li{Opportunities for improvement}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 6: Certification Audit (Weeks 37-42)}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Stage 1 Audit}: Documentation review, readiness assessment}
\li{Address Stage 1 findings}
\li{\strong{Stage 2 Audit}: On-site assessment of ISMS effectiveness}
\li{Resolve any nonconformities (major NCRs require re-audit)}
\li{Receive ISO 27001 certification (valid for 3 years)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 7: Continual Improvement (Ongoing)}
\ol{
\li{Annual surveillance audits (Years 1 and 2)}
\li{Recertification audit (Year 3)}
\li{Regular risk reassessment and control effectiveness reviews}
\li{Incident-driven improvements and lessons learned integration}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Key Artifacts}
\ul{
\li{ISMS Scope Document}
\li{Information Security Policy}
\li{Risk Assessment Methodology}
\li{Risk Register and Risk Treatment Plan}
\li{Statement of Applicability (SoA)}
\li{Internal Audit Reports}
\li{Management Review Minutes}
\li{Corrective Action Register}
\li{Metrics and KPI Dashboard}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Pitfalls}
\ul{
\li{Scope too broad or too narrow, leading to audit complications}
\li{Treating ISO 27001 as a checkbox exercise rather than embedding into business processes}
\li{Insufficient top management involvement and commitment}
\li{Failing to maintain documented evidence of control operation}
\li{Not performing regular risk reassessments as the threat landscape changes}
\li{Ignoring the 11 new controls in the 2022 edition during transition}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Integration Points}
\ul{
\li{\strong{ISO 27002:2022}: Detailed implementation guidance for Annex A controls}
\li{\strong{ISO 27005}: Information security risk management methodology}
\li{\strong{ISO 27017}: Cloud security controls}
\li{\strong{ISO 27018}: Protection of PII in cloud services}
\li{\strong{ISO 27701}: Privacy Information Management System (PIMS) extension}
\li{\strong{NIST CSF 2.0}: Cross-mapping for dual compliance}
\li{\strong{SOC 2}: Overlapping trust service criteria}
}
}

